column34:
Some of the material was absolutely useful. I think the emphasis on regression models wasn't nearly enough. I would've preferred having more time to focus on it. I think the focus on the more conceptual parts felt a bit unhelpful. There is some level of required understanding, but going through the specific differences in the notation for population v sample, or having a reading check question on the steps of collecting data felt unrelated.

It felt inconsistent/confusing with what levels of coding we should have memorized. I'd be curious to ask what proportions of each student's study sheet consisted of. I had maybe 30% of one side just covering the 5 Named Graphs and the additional code and nuances each has.

column34: I think that having more sample exams or questions similar to the exam would be much more useful, as it helps with not only preparing for the exam but also preparing for content review and important topics. For example, spending time on Simpson's paradox was important for understanding, but the emphasis made it seem like it would be on the exam. I also wish that the application questions on the exam resembled the code that we are exposed to in the class slides or activities, rather than excess code on the website.
